91
00:04:14,185 --> 00:04:15,465
How much is it gonna cost to make the game?

92
00:04:16,266 --> 00:04:17,466
How much money is the game gonna make?

93
00:04:18,466 --> 00:04:19,347
And when's that gonna happen?

94
00:04:20,327 --> 00:04:22,848
So I am very confident that a number of people

95
00:04:22,888 --> 00:04:23,948
sitting in this room going,

96
00:04:24,688 --> 00:04:27,669
well, duh, it's a business, of course I have those things.

97
00:04:28,349 --> 00:04:30,150
But I'm also very confident that a number of people

98
00:04:30,210 --> 00:04:31,610
sitting in this room going,

99
00:04:32,876 --> 00:04:36,299
Ah, I don't actually have answers to every one of those questions.

100
00:04:37,340 --> 00:04:39,962
You must. Otherwise, you're not running a business,

101
00:04:40,422 --> 00:04:44,345
you're not making a project, you are engaging in an act of faith.

102
00:04:45,246 --> 00:04:47,347
And if you have a team, that's irresponsible.

103
00:04:48,708 --> 00:04:50,930
So you should be able to answer every one of those questions

104
00:04:52,111 --> 00:04:55,333
without referring to documentation. That has to be the bones

105
00:04:56,014 --> 00:04:58,075
of the thing you build to survive gravity.

106
00:05:02,691 --> 00:05:05,253
So the reason that you are here today is,

107
00:05:05,453 --> 00:05:07,594
unless you are press or unless you've strayed in here

108
00:05:07,614 --> 00:05:09,235
looking for the bathroom, which is on the left,

109
00:05:09,835 --> 00:05:12,577
then it's because you want to run a studio

110
00:05:12,717 --> 00:05:14,138
or you are already running a studio.

111
00:05:16,599 --> 00:05:20,702
This is why people want to run studios, indie studios.

112
00:05:21,943 --> 00:05:23,824
But that's just the how, it's not the why.

113
00:05:25,045 --> 00:05:26,685
If you spend eight hours a day,

114
00:05:26,786 --> 00:05:28,206
five days a week making games,

115
00:05:29,562 --> 00:05:33,003
Making games is a really kind of broad category of activity.

116
00:05:33,063 --> 00:05:34,183
What do you actually want to spend

117
00:05:34,203 --> 00:05:35,444
those eight hours a day doing?

118
00:05:36,484 --> 00:05:39,765
Managing people, coding, drawing, designing,

119
00:05:40,585 --> 00:05:42,526
marketing stuff, giving talks at conferences.

120
00:05:44,586 --> 00:05:48,547
Often, people seize onto an inspiration,

121
00:05:48,607 --> 00:05:50,708
a studio that they want to be like.

122
00:05:50,908 --> 00:05:53,529
You see people do good work, you want to do similar work.

123
00:05:53,849 --> 00:05:56,590
You see people out in the industry

124
00:05:57,010 --> 00:05:58,030
who seem to be having a good time.

125
00:05:58,050 --> 00:05:58,810
You want to be like them.

126
00:06:00,161 --> 00:06:01,282
This is a good place to start,

127
00:06:02,584 --> 00:06:04,806
but you can't replicate a studio

128
00:06:04,866 --> 00:06:06,608
by looking at the shape of it from the outside.

129
00:06:06,648 --> 00:06:10,052
If you put wings and a nose and a tail

130
00:06:10,152 --> 00:06:11,394
and a cockpit on something

131
00:06:11,414 --> 00:06:13,236
without thinking about how it actually works,

132
00:06:14,657 --> 00:06:18,802
what you get is unlikely to clock much time in the air.

133
00:06:20,244 --> 00:06:21,525
Here's a concrete example of what I mean.

134
00:06:22,689 --> 00:06:26,153
I'm going to show you a quote, something somebody said to me back in about 2010, 2011.

135
00:06:26,393 --> 00:06:32,940
They weren't a stupid person at all, they just didn't know what it was like being at Failbetter.

136
00:06:34,802 --> 00:06:40,088
At that point, Failbetter barely generated any revenue at all,

137
00:06:40,969 --> 00:06:44,693
let alone, you know, floating happily through life with sheer creativity.

138
00:06:46,438 --> 00:06:50,000
It's very easy to look at a studio from the outside

139
00:06:50,060 --> 00:06:53,602
that has published games and that has like a website

140
00:06:53,622 --> 00:06:54,683
where they look kind of professional,

141
00:06:55,083 --> 00:06:56,564
where people show up at conferences with badges

142
00:06:56,724 --> 00:06:58,505
and assume that things are serene.

143
00:06:58,525 --> 00:07:00,386
And if you copy them, you'll end up in the right place.

144
00:07:01,546 --> 00:07:02,547
It's very dangerous to do that.

145
00:07:03,527 --> 00:07:05,328
Even when you have a more detailed idea

146
00:07:05,489 --> 00:07:08,550
of what you want to do on a project,

147
00:07:09,571 --> 00:07:12,352
again, if you try to copy the detailed idea

148
00:07:12,652 --> 00:07:15,774
without understanding why decisions have been taken.

149
00:07:17,660 --> 00:07:19,482
you can end up with something that isn't fit for purpose.

150
00:07:21,724 --> 00:07:24,466
This was my business plan, if you can call it that,

151
00:07:24,686 --> 00:07:26,027
in 2009 when I found a Failbetter.

152
00:07:26,047 --> 00:07:28,129
Here I am.

153
00:07:28,269 --> 00:07:29,110
Has 10 million players.

154
00:07:29,791 --> 00:07:30,711
It's got a shit story.

155
00:07:31,632 --> 00:07:33,934
So I'll make a game that's kind of a social Facebook RPG,

156
00:07:33,954 --> 00:07:35,595
because that's what people were making in 2009.

157
00:07:35,816 --> 00:07:37,577
It'll have a great story.

158
00:07:38,078 --> 00:07:39,118
So it'll do twice as well.

159
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:43,551
Yeah, so that didn't happen,

160
00:07:44,672 --> 00:07:46,153
because I completely failed to understand

161
00:07:46,433 --> 00:07:47,955
why people were making social RPGs

162
00:07:47,995 --> 00:07:50,336
and what made some social RPGs successful.

163
00:07:51,197 --> 00:07:53,659
As it happens, I'm really glad I didn't,

164
00:07:54,379 --> 00:07:56,020
because if we had got 20 million players,

165
00:07:56,120 --> 00:07:58,502
I'd have ended up trying to run a business

166
00:07:58,522 --> 00:08:00,704
that was servicing 20 million players and not making games.

167
00:08:01,084 --> 00:08:02,325
But there was no chance of that happening,

168
00:08:02,405 --> 00:08:04,206
because I was doing this.

169
00:08:07,389 --> 00:08:11,191
So this is a pithy insight I am indebted to Lottie for.

170
00:08:12,747 --> 00:08:15,247
You wouldn't sit down and say, I'm making a game

171
00:08:15,267 --> 00:08:17,188
and it's gonna be kind of like that game.

172
00:08:17,748 --> 00:08:18,368
I mean, you might,

173
00:08:18,428 --> 00:08:21,529
but it's probably not gonna be a great strategy.

174
00:08:22,249 --> 00:08:23,129
You want design pillars,

175
00:08:23,149 --> 00:08:27,190
you want key goals for what you're doing.

176
00:08:27,890 --> 00:08:30,871
You want reference points for what you're trying to do.

177
00:08:32,351 --> 00:08:33,752
So do the same with your business.

178
00:08:34,212 --> 00:08:35,052
You're building a studio,

179
00:08:35,092 --> 00:08:37,652
think about what you want the studio to be and do

180
00:08:37,993 --> 00:08:38,853
and build it around that.

181
00:08:40,513 --> 00:08:43,974
Here are some contenders for design pillars for a studio.

182
00:08:45,415 --> 00:08:46,335
Take a moment to look at this

183
00:08:46,395 --> 00:08:49,555
and see which of these things apply to you.

184
00:08:50,936 --> 00:08:55,777
All of these are perfectly decent ways to run a studio,

185
00:08:55,797 --> 00:08:56,957
perfectly decent things to focus on.

186
00:08:59,038 --> 00:09:02,078
So me, broadly speaking, I'm in the left-hand column,

187
00:09:02,698 --> 00:09:04,239
which isn't a particular category,

188
00:09:04,279 --> 00:09:05,899
it's just a list of things that I like.

189
00:09:06,099 --> 00:09:07,179
I do enjoy the biz side of things,

190
00:09:07,199 --> 00:09:08,200
but it's not my main focus.

191
00:09:09,478 --> 00:09:11,979
I like getting hands-on, more about that later.

192
00:09:12,520 --> 00:09:15,741
I'm a story guy, and I really enjoy developing in the open.

193
00:09:17,141 --> 00:09:20,423
I like crowdfunding, I like working with the community

194
00:09:20,463 --> 00:09:23,544
to get feedback and to find out how to improve games.

195
00:09:24,264 --> 00:09:26,965
I find it very validating and I find it a very clear way

196
00:09:27,005 --> 00:09:27,986
of fixing my mistakes.

197
00:09:29,446 --> 00:09:31,347
On the other hand, take someone like Subset Games

198
00:09:31,407 --> 00:09:33,448
who made Into the Reach and FTL.

199
00:09:35,073 --> 00:09:42,496
They do great work, they are world-class devs, and Justin Ma, one of the founders, told me

200
00:09:42,516 --> 00:09:46,857
a couple of years ago that they are never going to run, he said at the time, another

201
00:09:46,877 --> 00:09:48,437
Kickstarter after the FTL one.

202
00:09:48,998 --> 00:09:54,199
The FTL Kickstarter was successful, they made a really good game, but they just didn't enjoy

203
00:09:54,339 --> 00:09:55,780
developing in the spotlight.

204
00:09:57,646 --> 00:09:59,128
So they went away and they made Into the Breach

205
00:09:59,248 --> 00:10:01,370
over four years and polished it in the dark

206
00:10:01,390 --> 00:10:03,092
till it glowed like a star and they released it,

207
00:10:03,492 --> 00:10:06,015
which is again a perfectly acceptable way of doing it

208
00:10:06,556 --> 00:10:08,538
if that's the kind of thing you want to do.

209
00:10:08,558 --> 00:10:11,622
So think about how you want to approach your work.

210
00:10:12,162 --> 00:10:13,764
There are a dozen ways to skin a cat.

211
00:10:15,024 --> 00:10:17,525
Think about it not just now, but over the next decade.

212
00:10:18,065 --> 00:10:20,486
What you want to do today may not be

213
00:10:20,546 --> 00:10:21,586
what you want to do next year.

214
00:10:21,606 --> 00:10:22,426
This caught me out.

215
00:10:23,227 --> 00:10:25,607
So always keep an eye on what you're in this for,

216
00:10:25,687 --> 00:10:27,908
what you want to spend your eight hours a day doing.

217
00:10:30,289 --> 00:10:33,229
These are the design pillars for Failbetter

218
00:10:33,249 --> 00:10:34,610
that we iterated towards.

219
00:10:35,030 --> 00:10:37,631
2015, this was a slide at the all hands end of year thing.

220
00:10:39,111 --> 00:10:42,172
The key things here were everybody keeps their job.

221
00:10:43,707 --> 00:10:46,508
Everybody enjoys their job and we do great.

222
00:10:46,588 --> 00:10:49,349
So the third one is the aspirational thing

223
00:10:49,589 --> 00:10:51,129
you put at the end of a mission statement.

224
00:10:51,209 --> 00:10:53,530
Because God help me, this is a mission statement.

225
00:10:54,390 --> 00:10:56,771
Design pillars for a studio are a mission statement.

226
00:10:57,971 --> 00:10:59,492
When you hear the phrase mission statement,

227
00:11:00,692 --> 00:11:03,193
you tend to think it's some bullshit on a plaque somewhere.

228
00:11:04,133 --> 00:11:06,694
And frequently, it is some bullshit on a plaque somewhere

229
00:11:07,334 --> 00:11:08,975
because it's what people have compromised

230
00:11:09,015 --> 00:11:10,715
to fit on a plaque on the wall of an office.

231
00:11:12,237 --> 00:11:14,338
So what you want in your mission statement

232
00:11:14,398 --> 00:11:16,360
or your design pillars is a clear idea

233
00:11:16,420 --> 00:11:17,461
of what your priorities are.

234
00:11:18,061 --> 00:11:19,422
Don't make your mission statement,

235
00:11:19,462 --> 00:11:20,683
we are going to succeed,

236
00:11:21,624 --> 00:11:22,925
because everybody wants to succeed.

237
00:11:23,105 --> 00:11:25,347
Nobody puts a mission statement on their wall saying,

238
00:11:25,567 --> 00:11:27,068
we are the kind of company that fucks up.

239
00:11:29,570 --> 00:11:30,931
Think in terms of priorities.

240
00:11:31,432 --> 00:11:34,574
These are those things, restated,

241
00:11:34,634 --> 00:11:36,736
safety, fun, and profit, in that order.

242
00:11:36,916 --> 00:11:37,697
And that's important.

243
00:11:37,737 --> 00:11:38,978
There's no reason those three things

244
00:11:39,018 --> 00:11:39,938
needed to be in that order.

245
00:11:41,883 --> 00:11:43,645
We really wanted to make sure everyone stayed employed.

246
00:11:43,926 --> 00:11:45,949
We wanted to make sure people had a good time.

247
00:11:46,309 --> 00:11:48,492
And after that, money's nice.

248
00:11:49,354 --> 00:11:50,836
There's a difference between going for the kind of money

249
00:11:50,856 --> 00:11:52,358
that keeps everyone paid and the kind of money

250
00:11:52,398 --> 00:11:53,820
that buys you a big gold house.

251
00:11:55,805 --> 00:11:57,707
These are the priorities at Weather Factory,

252
00:11:58,147 --> 00:11:59,148
which Lottie and I run now.

253
00:11:59,388 --> 00:12:01,530
And you'll notice we switched the top two,

254
00:12:01,630 --> 00:12:03,112
because Weather Factory is quite well funded

255
00:12:03,412 --> 00:12:05,734
and it's got a very small team, so it's a low burn.

256
00:12:06,194 --> 00:12:09,037
The whole idea was to do a bunch of interesting experiments

